definition.value: A set of neologistic pronouns created by Werner Low in 1977.
A set of neologistic pronouns created by Jeffrey J. Smith in 1977.
A set of neologistic pronouns created by Aline Hoffman in 1979.
A set of neologistic pronouns created by Jerome Ch'en in 1979.
A set of neologistic pronouns created by Steven Schaufele in 1984.
A transgender woman who is heterosexual, i.e. attracted to men.
A transgender man who is heterosexual, i.e. attracted to women.
A man who is cisgender and heterosexual.
A woman who is cisgender and heterosexual.
An ethnic group native to England who speak the English language.
A Romance ethnic group who are identified with the country of France. This connection may be ethnic, legal, historical, or cultural.
A surgical specialty concerned with surgical treatment of the diseases of the urinary tract and urogenital system.
A dialect employed by a population for public communications, or as the dialect of a language that has undergone codification of grammar and usage.
A dialect that has not historically benefited from the institutional support or sanction that a standard dialect has.

The variety of English that has undergone regularization and is associated with formal schooling, language assessment, and official print publications, such as public-service announcements and newspapers of record, etc.
Dialects organized by the language they belong to.
Any of various dialects of the English language.
The set of varieties of the English language native to Great Britain.
The set of varieties of the English language native to the United States.
Any of various dialects of English spoken primarily in North America.
Any of various dialects of English spoken primarily in Europe.
The set of varieties of the English language native to Canada.
Any of various dialects of English spoken primarily in Oceania.

The set of varieties of the English language native to Australia. Although English has no official status in the Constitution, Australian English is the country's national and de facto official language as it is the first language of the majority of the population.
Any of various dialects of English spoken primarily in Asia.
The regional variety of the English language spoken in the Republic of India, and among the Indian diaspora elsewhere in the world.
A Bangladeshi variety of English heavily influenced by Bengali.
A variety of English principally used in Nepal that is heavily influenced by Nepalese.
The group of English language varieties spoken and written in Pakistan.
The variety of the English language as it is spoken in Sri Lanka.
Any of various dialects of English spoken primarily in Africa.
The set of English dialects native to South Africans.
A dialect of English spoken in Nigeria.
Any variety of English native to the Philippines, including those used by the media and the vast majority of educated Filipinos.
The set of varieties of the English language native to Scotland.
The set of varieties of the English language native to Wales.
The variant of the English language spoken and written by most English-speaking New Zealanders.
The variety of the English language spoken in Singapore, of which there are two main forms, Standard Singapore English and Singapore Colloquial English (better known as Singlish).
Any of various dialects of American English specific to particular ethnic groups or racial categories.
The set of English dialects primarily spoken by most Black people in the United States.
The variety of English natively spoken, particularly in urban communities, by most working- and middle-class African Americans and some Black Canadians.

The variety of American English that has undergone regularization and is associated with formal schooling, language assessment, and official print publications, such as public-service announcements and newspapers of record, etc.
Any of various regional dialects of American English.

A regional dialect or collection of dialects of American English spoken throughout the Southern United States, though increasingly in more rural areas and primarily by White Southerners. The dialect is commonly known in the United States simply as Southern, while formal, much more recent terms within American linguistics include Southern White Vernacular English and Rural White Southern English.
Discrimination against person's of a given ethnicity or ethnicities.
Discrimination based on age.

Unfair treatment of an individual based solely on their use of language. This use of language may include the individual's native language or other characteristics of the person's speech, such as an accent, the size of vocabulary (whether the person uses complex and varied words), modality, and syntax. It may also involve a person's ability or inability to use one language instead of another.

Treating of a person or group differently because of the particular beliefs which they hold about a religion. This includes instances when adherents of different religions, denominations or non-religions are treated unequally due to their particular beliefs, either before the law or in institutional settings, such as employment or housing.
Discrimination against a person or persons based on socially constructed racial categories.
A form of institutional discrimination against individuals of a given group which has the effect of restricting their opportunities.
